[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Smith is a pleasant 86-year-old gentleman from Sale City Pennsylvania. We are seeing him today to discuss treatment recommendations following resected node-positive adenocarcinoma.  His oncology history is as follows:
1.  August 12, 2010:  Admitted to the hospital with weakness, leg pain, and tiredness; at that time was found to be anemic, and hemoglobin 6.4; underwent blood transfusions.
2.  August 31, 2010:  Return to see primary-care provider with similar complaints, at that time recommending further work-up that would be difficult to perform as an outpatient, and patient was therefore admitted to the hospital.
3.  September 1, 2010:  Colonoscopy performed to the ileal cecal valve noting sigmoid diverticulosis as well as a polyp in the descending/sigmoid colon.  The polyp was positive for tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  At the hepatic flexure, an ulcerated mass was identified that was biopsied.  This was positive for invasive adenocarcinoma, moderately to poorly-differentiated.
4.  September 2, 2010:  CT abdomen and pelvis noting abnormal mural thickening at the hepatic flexure; malignant adenopathy in the adjacent mesentery, retroperitoneum, right iliac chain, and Foramen of Winslow.  There is interstitial thickening of the lower lungs, possibly from edema or fibrosis.  CEA was noted to be 4.1
5.  September 15, 2010:  Dr. Hutchinson performed a right hemicolectomy.  The pathology was positive for undifferentiated, grade 4 (of 4), adenocarcinoma that extended through the muscularis propria into pericolonic fat.  All surgical resected margins are negative.  Of 15 regional lymph nodes removed, 8 were positive for metastatic disease.  Microsatellite instability testing notes instability in five of five informative markers (pT3, pN2).
Today, Mr. Smith states that he feels the best he has in several years.  His main complaints are feeling cold and altered taste.  Patient states that he does remain well-hydrated, drinking plenty of fluids.  He has lost over 22 pounds since the summer, reports that he has lost approximately 1 pound over the last two-weeks; states that food does not taste like it had previously, does think that this is improving, also reports some early satiety.  He denies any nausea or vomiting.  He reports that his energy level has certainly increased, stating that he is doing activities now that he has not been able to do for quite some time.  Reports that he has a daily bowel movement that is absent of any blood or mucus; patient reports that he has frequent urination, unable to quantify how many times he uses the bathroom; states that he does get up in the middle of the night to urinate.  He denies chest pain, shortness-of-breath, lower-extremity edema, night sweats, or elevated temperature.

